00:00:06.190 --> 00:00:10.100
CAROL FULP: Our organization
is a diversity consulting

00:00:10.100 --> 00:00:11.340
organization.

00:00:11.340 --> 00:00:15.290
And over the years,
we have actually

00:00:15.290 --> 00:00:22.070
provided leadership development
for 4,000 executives

00:00:22.070 --> 00:00:23.930
and professionals of color.

00:00:23.930 --> 00:00:30.680
It's been a journey for me
being at the partnership.

00:00:30.680 --> 00:00:35.360
What led me to the
partnership was really

00:00:35.360 --> 00:00:37.700
when President
Obama appointed me

00:00:37.700 --> 00:00:42.950
to be the US representative
to the United Nations

00:00:42.950 --> 00:00:45.860
for the 65th General Assembly.

00:00:45.860 --> 00:00:48.650
And it was a really
humbling experience.

00:00:48.650 --> 00:00:51.170
Each year, the president
has the opportunity

00:00:51.170 --> 00:00:56.210
to appoint someone outside
of the State Department

00:00:56.210 --> 00:00:58.580
to be a part of the delegation.

00:00:58.580 --> 00:01:03.980
And this was a role that Eleanor
Roosevelt filled, Coretta Scott

00:01:03.980 --> 00:01:09.440
King filled, and then I had
the opportunity to fill.

00:01:09.440 --> 00:01:15.710
So you can imagine how
humbling this experience was.

00:01:15.710 --> 00:01:23.030
And when you stand up on the
stage of the United Nations,

00:01:23.030 --> 00:01:30.230
at that iconic podium,
and you look out

00:01:30.230 --> 00:01:33.950
amongst the sea
of ambassadors, it

00:01:33.950 --> 00:01:39.170
hits you that the
world is primarily

00:01:39.170 --> 00:01:47.760
black and brown and yellow by
the ambassadors that you see.

00:01:47.760 --> 00:01:50.690
And so when I came
back to Boston,

00:01:50.690 --> 00:01:58.880
I wanted to help Boston to be
more reflective of the United

00:01:58.880 --> 00:02:00.350
Nations.

00:02:00.350 --> 00:02:03.260
And so I left my
job at John Hancock

00:02:03.260 --> 00:02:08.419
and took on this role at
the partnership as CEO

00:02:08.419 --> 00:02:14.970
in order to help companies
advance in diversity.

00:02:14.970 --> 00:02:19.220
And so that's what I've been
doing these last six years.

00:02:19.220 --> 00:02:24.360
And that's what led me to write
"Success through Diversity."

00:02:24.360 --> 00:02:26.960
Now, we were talking earlier.

00:02:26.960 --> 00:02:31.340
And while I might be
passionate about diversity,

00:02:31.340 --> 00:02:34.940
I only want to
approach diversity

00:02:34.940 --> 00:02:37.680
from a business perspective.

00:02:37.680 --> 00:02:41.040
I don't want to approach
it from my passion.

00:02:41.040 --> 00:02:45.990
I want to approach it from,
why is it good for business?

00:02:45.990 --> 00:02:52.610
And so thus the tagline, why
the most inclusive companies

00:02:52.610 --> 00:02:53.930
will win.

00:02:53.930 --> 00:02:56.310
Because it's about winning.

00:02:56.310 --> 00:03:00.710
So let me share
with you this story.

00:03:00.710 --> 00:03:04.340
"Toy giant Mattel
is another example

00:03:04.340 --> 00:03:08.510
of a company that catapulted
its business forward

00:03:08.510 --> 00:03:12.370
by appealing to a
diverse marketplace.

00:03:12.370 --> 00:03:18.200
For decades, since its debut
in 1959, the Barbie doll--

00:03:18.200 --> 00:03:23.240
flawlessly thin, high
heeled, and white skinned--

00:03:23.240 --> 00:03:28.610
was a cultural sensation, and
one of the world's best selling

00:03:28.610 --> 00:03:30.290
toys.

00:03:30.290 --> 00:03:35.360
Over the years, Mattel
modestly diversified

00:03:35.360 --> 00:03:39.680
the toy's occupations
and ethnicities,

00:03:39.680 --> 00:03:45.140
creating a Barbie business
woman, 1963, a Barbie

00:03:45.140 --> 00:03:51.770
astronaut, 1965, an
African-American Barbie, '67,

00:03:51.770 --> 00:03:55.940
and a Barbie surgeon, '73.

00:03:55.940 --> 00:04:00.110
Mattel's efforts
enabled the doll

00:04:00.110 --> 00:04:08.060
to maintain about a 90% market
share in girl-oriented toys

00:04:08.060 --> 00:04:11.630
for most of the 20th century.

00:04:11.630 --> 00:04:17.930
By the mid 2000s, Barbie's
dominance and brand appeal

00:04:17.930 --> 00:04:20.300
began to lag.

00:04:20.300 --> 00:04:25.340
After four straight quarters
of plummeting sales,

00:04:25.340 --> 00:04:31.100
it was no longer the
best selling doll.

00:04:31.100 --> 00:04:35.030
The brand was losing
relevance, said

00:04:35.030 --> 00:04:39.290
Lisa McKnight, senior
vice president at Mattel.

00:04:39.290 --> 00:04:44.150
We knew we had to
change the conversation.

00:04:44.150 --> 00:04:47.390
A creative team
within Mattel worked

00:04:47.390 --> 00:04:53.210
for two years under the
secretive code, Project Dawn,

00:04:53.210 --> 00:04:58.760
began Barbie's modern makeover,
designing a more inclusive set

00:04:58.760 --> 00:05:02.510
of dolls that more
accurately reflected

00:05:02.510 --> 00:05:08.320
the size and complexion
of America's children.

00:05:08.320 --> 00:05:15.280
In 2015, Mattel unleashed
the fruits of Project Dawn,

00:05:15.280 --> 00:05:21.790
launching a new generation of
dolls, complete with curvy body

00:05:21.790 --> 00:05:30.790
sizes, 23 hair colors, 22
hairdos, 18 eye colors,

00:05:30.790 --> 00:05:34.840
and an array of skin tones.

00:05:34.840 --> 00:05:40.480
This product launch, Mattel's
most significant rebranding

00:05:40.480 --> 00:05:47.380
effort to date, has proven
revitalizing and lucrative.

00:05:47.380 --> 00:05:51.340
Parents and children
alike flocked

00:05:51.340 --> 00:05:58.600
to the ethnically, racially, and
bodily diverse product lines.

00:05:58.600 --> 00:06:03.820
Barbie became the most
diverse doll product line

00:06:03.820 --> 00:06:08.350
and at the Toy Industry
Association's annual Toy

00:06:08.350 --> 00:06:13.150
of the Year awards
in 2017, the company

00:06:13.150 --> 00:06:18.730
won the coveted Doll
of the Year Award.

00:06:18.730 --> 00:06:21.520
This new generation
of Barbies wouldn't

00:06:21.520 --> 00:06:26.110
have been possible without
a diverse workforce

00:06:26.110 --> 00:06:28.270
inside Mattel.

00:06:28.270 --> 00:06:32.890
To help design a culturally
sensitive and compelling

00:06:32.890 --> 00:06:36.820
black Barbie, for
example, the company's

00:06:36.820 --> 00:06:40.510
marketing teams
consulted with Mattel's

00:06:40.510 --> 00:06:44.620
African-American
forum, the toy maker's

00:06:44.620 --> 00:06:49.300
African-American
employee resource group.

00:06:49.300 --> 00:06:55.330
Members helped get the doll's
names, skin tone, and hair

00:06:55.330 --> 00:06:57.790
just right.

00:06:57.790 --> 00:07:00.040
They asked us very
candid questions

00:07:00.040 --> 00:07:02.080
about the look of the doll.

00:07:02.080 --> 00:07:04.420
Did they get the
skin tone right?

00:07:04.420 --> 00:07:06.040
What about the nose?

00:07:06.040 --> 00:07:08.890
And the hair, said
David Simmons,

00:07:08.890 --> 00:07:12.400
associate manager
of account planning

00:07:12.400 --> 00:07:16.030
and a member of the ERG group.

00:07:16.030 --> 00:07:21.010
This was important,
because consumers roundly

00:07:21.010 --> 00:07:26.620
criticized the 1967
African-American

00:07:26.620 --> 00:07:32.950
Barbie, Colored Francie,
for her inauthenticity.

00:07:32.950 --> 00:07:36.610
Besides having a
darker skin tone,

00:07:36.610 --> 00:07:42.040
she lacked any bodily
features or hairstyles

00:07:42.040 --> 00:07:45.910
typical of African-Americans.

00:07:45.910 --> 00:07:50.860
As African-American Tom
Burrell, a diversity advertising

00:07:50.860 --> 00:07:57.310
trailblazer famously
quipped, black people are not

00:07:57.310 --> 00:08:01.270
dark-skinned white people.

00:08:01.270 --> 00:08:06.010
A lack of authenticity plagued
previous Barbie diversity

00:08:06.010 --> 00:08:08.130
efforts as well.

00:08:08.130 --> 00:08:14.500
With the wheelchair-bound
Share a Smile Becky doll, 1997,

00:08:14.500 --> 00:08:19.810
lacking the correct proportions
to fit into her dream house

00:08:19.810 --> 00:08:22.810
elevator and the
computer engineer

00:08:22.810 --> 00:08:26.770
Barbie product
line requiring help

00:08:26.770 --> 00:08:30.250
from boys to actually code.

00:08:30.250 --> 00:08:36.940
However, for its 2016
line of gamer Barbies,

00:08:36.940 --> 00:08:41.559
Mattel drew on female
engineer leaders,

00:08:41.559 --> 00:08:47.860
such as Molly Proffitt, CEO
of Ker-Chunk Games, Julie Ann

00:08:47.860 --> 00:08:54.820
Crommett, entertainment industry
editor in chief at Google,

00:08:54.820 --> 00:08:59.650
and Kimberly Bryant,
founder of Black Girls Code,

00:08:59.650 --> 00:09:06.550
to help design a compelling
doll that resembled a real tech

00:09:06.550 --> 00:09:07.600
geek.

00:09:07.600 --> 00:09:13.840
These women advised Mattel
during their design process,

00:09:13.840 --> 00:09:17.140
ensuring the new
career game developer

00:09:17.140 --> 00:09:21.760
Barbie was authentic,
compelling, and would help

00:09:21.760 --> 00:09:26.890
inspire a new generation
of budding female computer

00:09:26.890 --> 00:09:31.120
scientists and STEM leaders.

00:09:31.120 --> 00:09:35.680
The computer has
JavaScript on it,

00:09:35.680 --> 00:09:39.970
and you can see various
instances of game engines

00:09:39.970 --> 00:09:43.270
on her laptop, said
one of the leaders,

00:09:43.270 --> 00:09:46.910
commenting on the new line.

00:09:46.910 --> 00:09:51.220
I really know the girls need
an icon that shows them they

00:09:51.220 --> 00:09:54.580
can be part of the tech space.

00:09:54.580 --> 00:09:57.490
And Barbie does that.

00:09:57.490 --> 00:10:00.670
She has the power
to tell girls they

00:10:00.670 --> 00:10:04.280
can be makers and builders.

00:10:04.280 --> 00:10:09.240
Even Barbie's companion, Ken,
received a totally diversity

00:10:09.240 --> 00:10:12.740
makeover in 2017.

00:10:12.740 --> 00:10:16.520
Prior to the new
iteration of Ken dolls,

00:10:16.520 --> 00:10:24.030
Barbie's plastic beau typically
sported blonde hair, blue eyes,

00:10:24.030 --> 00:10:26.600
and a chiseled figure.

00:10:26.600 --> 00:10:33.320
Revamped Ken comes, in
one case, with a man bun,

00:10:33.320 --> 00:10:41.420
while another sports a dad bod,
a Fortune article observed.

00:10:41.420 --> 00:10:44.720
All of this increased
diversity has

00:10:44.720 --> 00:10:49.100
led to more prosperity
for the company.

00:10:49.100 --> 00:10:56.630
Mattel's brunette Latina Barbie
with curves and brown eyes

00:10:56.630 --> 00:11:05.060
became the company's 2016 best
seller, a feat the Huntington

00:11:05.060 --> 00:11:10.760
Post senior reporter Emily
Peck calls, a clear victory

00:11:10.760 --> 00:11:13.670
for the toy maker giant.

00:11:13.670 --> 00:11:19.010
Following four years of
declines, sales of the dolls

00:11:19.010 --> 00:11:26.570
increased 7% in 2016,
earning nearly $1 billion

00:11:26.570 --> 00:11:35.660
for the company, certainly
proving that diversity sells."

