00:31:07.920 --> 00:31:11.942
And we want to make sure
that we want to set them up

00:31:11.942 --> 00:31:13.150
for success wherever they go.

00:31:13.150 --> 00:31:14.770
So whether they end up at Google
or they end up somewhere else,

00:31:14.770 --> 00:31:16.070
we want make sure they're
having a good experience

00:31:16.070 --> 00:31:18.480
and that when they get there,
they can really flourish.

00:31:18.480 --> 00:31:20.355
So there's a lot of
companies, I can imagine,

00:31:20.355 --> 00:31:22.462
that do pretty well
recruiting and retaining,

00:31:22.462 --> 00:31:24.170
but don't necessarily
see people of color

00:31:24.170 --> 00:31:26.205
moving up at the same
rate as other folks.

00:31:26.205 --> 00:31:27.830
Are there any companies
that you notice

00:31:27.830 --> 00:31:29.372
through your research
that are really

00:31:29.372 --> 00:31:32.120
good at promoting upward
mobility for people of color?

00:31:32.120 --> 00:31:34.730
CAROL FULP: The
company in Boston

00:31:34.730 --> 00:31:38.720
that I think does it
best is Eastern Bank.

00:31:38.720 --> 00:31:42.260
And that's because of
the executive leadership

00:31:42.260 --> 00:31:44.460
of that company.

00:31:44.460 --> 00:31:50.180
So Bob Rivers is
the chairman and CEO

00:31:50.180 --> 00:31:55.610
and is actually named
after Robert Kennedy,

00:31:55.610 --> 00:32:01.890
and so takes the issue of
diversity and inclusion

00:32:01.890 --> 00:32:07.730
very personally and
chose specifically,

00:32:07.730 --> 00:32:11.810
when expanding the
business, chose

00:32:11.810 --> 00:32:17.270
to expand in areas like
Lawrence and Lowell

00:32:17.270 --> 00:32:19.250
and was able to
make the business

00:32:19.250 --> 00:32:26.250
case for moving into those
socioeconomic depressed areas

00:32:26.250 --> 00:32:32.180
and build those
areas and make money.

00:32:32.180 --> 00:32:36.560
In that company, the
chair of the board

00:32:36.560 --> 00:32:39.730
is an African-American
woman and she

00:32:39.730 --> 00:32:48.730
succeeded an African-American
male chair, Bob's successor,

00:32:48.730 --> 00:32:52.420
the vice chair of the
board and president,

00:32:52.420 --> 00:32:56.200
is an African-American male.

00:32:56.200 --> 00:33:03.880
When he started, 90% of
the board was white male.

00:33:03.880 --> 00:33:11.950
And now, 50% of the board
are women, people of color,

00:33:11.950 --> 00:33:12.600
or LGBT.

00:33:15.310 --> 00:33:22.810
And that attracts a
whole set of people

00:33:22.810 --> 00:33:26.410
who want to be able
to work for a company,

00:33:26.410 --> 00:33:30.070
because the culture has shifted.

00:33:30.070 --> 00:33:35.380
So at the end of the day, what
is happening with diversity?

00:33:35.380 --> 00:33:38.830
It's all about culture.

00:33:38.830 --> 00:33:45.250
And you have to create a culture
where difference is valued,

00:33:45.250 --> 00:33:49.960
where difference
is not tolerated,

00:33:49.960 --> 00:33:53.800
where your difference
is an asset, where

00:33:53.800 --> 00:33:57.400
your difference
is valued and can

00:33:57.400 --> 00:34:02.440
be seen as a business value.

00:34:02.440 --> 00:34:05.980
And that is why
people will stay.

00:34:05.980 --> 00:34:10.100
And so when you're bringing
in these students--

00:34:10.100 --> 00:34:15.100
and if you don't have it, if
you don't have it all together,

00:34:15.100 --> 00:34:17.469
you ask them for their help.

00:34:17.469 --> 00:34:20.510
You say, here's
where we want to be.

00:34:20.510 --> 00:34:22.639
And we're not here yet.

00:34:22.639 --> 00:34:25.000
But we need your help.

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:28.120
And help us get there.

00:34:28.120 --> 00:34:34.600
Empower them to help
shape your culture.

00:34:34.600 --> 00:34:36.889
AUDIENCE: Thank you for coming.

